---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FAQ | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about workplace sexual harassment claims, EEOC procedure, settlements, severance traps, and taxes.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>1. What is the average sexual harassment settlement?</h2>
  <p>
    There is no single average that is useful, because the spread is enormous. Public EEOC data and verdict reporters suggest
    that uncontested hostile-environment matters resolved through mediation often land in the $30,000&ndash;$200,000 range. Cases
    involving constructive discharge or termination commonly settle for $50,000&ndash;$500,000. Egregious supervisor misconduct
    against high-earning employees at large employers with documentary evidence regularly exceeds $1 million, and class or
    pattern-and-practice matters reach seven and eight figures. The <a href="/">calculator</a> gives an educational range; a
    lawyer values the actual case.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Should I file with the EEOC or with my state agency?</h2>
  <p>
    Almost every state has a fair-employment agency that has a work-sharing agreement with the EEOC, so filing with one usually
    cross-files with the other. The strategic question is which agency&rsquo;s investigative posture and which statute&rsquo;s remedies
    favor your case. State law often beats Title VII because it has no damages cap (California FEHA, NY HRL), a longer statute
    of limitations, or a lower employee-count threshold for coverage. Many plaintiffs&rsquo; attorneys file with both and let the
    case proceed under the state statute. Talk to an attorney before choosing.
  </p>

  <h2>3. How are attorney fees paid in sexual harassment cases?</h2>
  <p>
    Almost always one of two ways. Most employment plaintiff&rsquo;s firms work on a <strong>contingency fee</strong>, typically
    33&ndash;40% of the recovery (higher if the case goes to trial). Title VII also has a <strong>fee-shifting</strong> provision at
    42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-5(k): a prevailing plaintiff can recover reasonable attorney fees from the employer, separate from the
    damages cap. In practice, the firm takes its contingency percentage and the fee-shifted award is part of the settlement
    structure; some firms credit the fee-shift against the contingency. Ask the question on day one.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Is my state &ldquo;at-will&rdquo; rule a problem for my harassment claim?</h2>
  <p>
    No. Every US state except Montana follows at-will employment, meaning either side can end the relationship at any time for
    any reason that is not unlawful. Sexual harassment, retaliation for opposing it, and discriminatory discharge are all unlawful
    reasons under Title VII and state statutes. At-will is a default rule, not a shield for discriminatory or retaliatory firings.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Am I protected from retaliation for complaining?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes, by 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3(a) and analogous state provisions. You are protected for opposing what you reasonably believe
    in good faith is unlawful conduct, even if the underlying conduct is later found to be lawful. The retaliation standard for
    adverse action is broader than for the underlying discrimination claim &mdash; anything that would dissuade a reasonable employee
    from complaining (<em>Burlington N. &amp; Santa Fe Ry. v. White</em>, 548 U.S. 53 (2006)). Retaliation claims regularly become
    the strongest part of a case.
  </p>

  <h2>6. My employer offered me severance. Should I sign?</h2>
  <p>
    Not without an employment lawyer reviewing it first. Severance agreements typically include a general release that waives
    all employment-related claims, including harassment and retaliation, in exchange for the severance payment. Once signed it is
    very hard to undo. Federal law (the Older Workers Benefit Protection Act) gives employees 40 or older a 21-day consideration
    window and a 7-day revocation window for ADEA waivers; many employers extend the consideration window for other claims as well.
    Use it. A lawyer can usually negotiate the severance number up materially when there is a credible harassment claim attached.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Is my harassment settlement taxable?</h2>
  <p>
    Mostly yes, and this is a frequent unpleasant surprise. Under 26 U.S.C. &sect; 104(a)(2), only damages received on account of
    <em>physical</em> injury or sickness are excluded from gross income. Emotional-distress damages from harassment, without an
    underlying physical injury, are taxable. Back pay and front pay are taxable as wages (subject to withholding). Punitive damages
    are taxable. The Section 162(q) provision added in 2017 also denies the employer a tax deduction for harassment settlements
    subject to NDA, which has shifted negotiation dynamics. Get a tax accountant involved before signing.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Can my employer require confidentiality in the settlement?</h2>
  <p>
    Less than it used to. The <strong>Speak Out Act of 2022</strong>, 42 U.S.C. &sect; 19401 et seq., voids pre-dispute nondisclosure
    and non-disparagement clauses that would block disclosure of sexual harassment or sexual assault claims. Many states (California,
    New York, New Jersey, Illinois, others) have layered on stricter limits, often voiding post-dispute NDAs that prevent disclosure
    of harassment facts even after settlement, or carving out exceptions for cooperation with government investigations and law
    enforcement. The amount paid can still be confidential; the underlying conduct increasingly cannot be.
  </p>

  <h2>9. Can a single incident be enough for a hostile work environment claim?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes, if it is severe enough. <em>Harris v. Forklift Systems</em> contemplates that an isolated act of sufficient severity &mdash;
    sexual assault is the textbook example &mdash; can alter the conditions of employment on its own. Most claims still rely on a
    course of conduct, but the &ldquo;severe or pervasive&rdquo; standard is disjunctive: severe alone, or pervasive alone, can suffice.
  </p>

  <h2>10. Do I have to use HR before going to the EEOC?</h2>
  <p>
    No. There is no federal requirement to exhaust internal remedies before filing an EEOC charge. However, failure to use a
    reasonable internal complaint procedure that existed and was communicated to you can support an employer&rsquo;s
    <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> affirmative defense in supervisor hostile-environment cases without tangible action. The
    common practical approach: file an internal complaint in writing, keep a copy, and file an EEOC charge if the response is
    inadequate or retaliatory. A lawyer will help you sequence this.
  </p>

  <h2>11. What if my employer is small &mdash; does Title VII still cover it?</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII covers private employers with 15 or more employees. Below that threshold, federal law does not apply, but state
    law often does. California FEHA covers employers with 5+ employees (and 1+ for harassment); New York covers all employers;
    Illinois covers all employers. Check your state agency&rsquo;s coverage chart before assuming there is no claim.
  </p>

  <h2>12. How long do I have to file?</h2>
  <p>
    Short windows that move quickly. <strong>EEOC charge: 180 days</strong> from the last act of harassment, extended to
    <strong>300 days</strong> in &ldquo;deferral&rdquo; states with their own fair-employment agency (most states).
    <strong>Federal-sector employees: 45 days</strong> to contact an EEO counselor. State agency windows vary &mdash; California
    is 3 years to file with the CRD; New York is 3 years for sexual harassment claims; New Jersey is 2 years for LAD lawsuits.
    Continuing-violation doctrine may pull older incidents into a timely charge, but do not rely on it without a lawyer&rsquo;s
    confirmation.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
